pr_title: SITL: update JSON backend and MATLAB example
pr_body:
The MATLAB copter now flys fine with no ekf issues, [see log](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1M6wS5w90Be8FowTFb2259GmbKwc4fxbj/view?usp=sharing)  

This update moves all the time snyc to the AP side simplifying the MATLAB code, any making future implementations easier. This does work with variable rate and speedup, however requires https://github.com/ArduPilot/ardupilot/pull/14518.

I have made a[ change to pnet.c](https://github.com/IamPete1/ardupilot/commit/cf7a31ee4aad4fd16dc3c9c6fa40f746219b40fc) to allow UDP to work without connecting, this means MATLAB just sends back to where it received from. This means Matlab will re-connect if you restart SITL. I have regenerate for Windows but it needs a re-gen on linux also.

The only other slightly odd thing is that I have to send the requested rate from AP as a int32 rather than a int16. MATLAB seems to not like receiving a number of bytes that is not a multiple of four. Maybe this is expected?

pr_title: SITL: add Simulink rover example
pr_body:
This adds a Simulink rover example along with a library for the required ArduPilot connection blocks.

Annoyingly Simulink files are versioned, these will only work on 2020a (or newer). I do have the option to back date for older versions but they make no guarantee that everything will still work.

The rover block used in this example requires the Robotics System Toolbox.

https://youtu.be/hTFyMrjwQlI

pr_title: SITL: JSON: support quaternion and euler attitude
pr_body:
This adds the ability for the JSON sitl backend to optionally receive things. This allows us to receive attitude as either a Euler angle or quaternion.

I have tested for Euler angles, @Williangalvani it would be great if you could check it for quaternion.

If this works it needs a short up date to the read me. Would be quite easy to add in more optional fields, airspeed being a obvious one. 

Currently there is no way to tell what it is receiving, not sure what we can do for optional fields. We could print what we got on the first connect.

pr_title: SITL: add rangefinder and use in JSON backend
pr_body:
I was quite surprised we did not have a rangefinder SITL backed. We have lots designed for testing drivers, but none that could be used with data from a simulator. 

This adds that. 

I have added support for all rotations, however this does mean were carrying a 42 float array in two places (SITL only). Maybe we could cut this down, the JSON backend only supports the 6 major directions.

Tested using MATLAB, I have also added a new print to the JSON backed that tells you what it is receiving, this is nice now we have more optional fields.

pr_title: SITL: add rangefinder and use in JSON backend
pr_body:
I was quite surprised we did not have a rangefinder SITL backed. We have lots designed for testing drivers, but none that could be used with data from a simulator. 

This adds that. 

I have added support for all rotations, however this does mean were carrying a 42 float array in two places (SITL only). Maybe we could cut this down, the JSON backend only supports the 6 major directions.

Tested using MATLAB, I have also added a new print to the JSON backed that tells you what it is receiving, this is nice now we have more optional fields.

pr_title: Quick Tune: PID 'auto manual' tune and oscillation detection
pr_body:
This is a auto oscillation detection algorithm that can scale back the gains to stop oscillation. Needs testing on more vehicles and in real life. This is a demo:

https://youtu.be/goSFD2A3qfM

This is a vid that explains the methodology before I did the  AP implementation.    

https://youtu.be/3Q1a2skm17g

I suspect this will probability be fine to leave running all the time on most vehicles (currently there is no way to switch it off!), the issue is more likely that it is not sensitive enough rather than the other way. There is quite a lot that can be done to change the sensitivity with the various filter values and thresholds, I have not found a good way to pick them yet tho.

In testing I just ran three at once on each aixs with a different filter frequency, this worked quite well however its hard to say if its worth the extra cpu/memory cost. Again we can do a better job using nicer filters, but this requires a keeping  buffers of past values. 

The next step will be a [Ziegler Nichols](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ziegler%E2%80%93Nichols_method) based 'quick tune'.
